summary.seg: This manuscript is a Psalter, probably copied in the second half of the 12th century. The Psalms are followed by the Odes, the sequence of hymns excerpted from various Biblical books, also known as canticles, which in the Orthodox tradition constitute a separate book of the Bible. The first nine of these are the basis for the canons which are a central component of Orthodox hymnography. Since the end of manuscript has been lost, it is unclear whether it contained only this basic set of nine or the full set of fifteen Odes.

The sequence of psalms was traditionally divided into a sequence of twenty divisions known as kathismata (sessions), marked in Psalters to indicate the points at which a break could be taken in the chanting of the text. In this manuscript the beginning of each is marked with a headpiece. Each kathisma was composed of three shorter parts, the transition between them being marked by the word δόξα. Unusually, the accompanying rubric here includes a specification of the hour of the day at which each kathisma was to be chanted. At the end of each kathisma appear troparia (short hymns) and prayers. This was a common feature of Psalters, with much variety in the specific hymns and prayers in each. More unusually, in this manuscript troparia are also included at the end of each doxa. This is one of the oldest Psalters in which this feature occurs (Parpulov, Byzantine Psalter, p. 60 n. 57).

The manuscript has suffered considerable damage, losing many folios and parts of others. Many damaged folios were repaired at some point with paper patches, on which substitute text was written to replace what had been lost. A few entirely lost folios were replaced with paper leaves. These have since been removed from the manuscript and are preserved alongside it. The surviving folios appear to have been severely disordered in the past, leading to apparent confusion in the 19th-century foliation. Some folio numbers have been repeated, and where this occurs one of the duplicate numbers has been marked with an asterisk; these marks have also been added to many other folio numbers.

supportDesc.foliation: The manuscript is foliated with the numbers [i-iv] + 34-39, 42-47, 49-88, 90-95, 97-112, 113*-118*, 119, 121*-131*, 129-144, 146, 148*-158*, 160*-164*, 166*-168*, 165-188, 190-195, 197-211, 213-219, 221-248, 253-268, 271-274, 278-300, 307-314, 317-340, 342*-347*, 351*-360* + [v-viii], in pencil, in Arabic numerals, recto, upper right. Folio numbers 1-33, 40-41, 48, 89, 96, 120, 145, 159*, 165*, 189, 196, 212, 220, 249-252, 269-270, 269-270, 275-277, 301-306, 315-316, 341*, 348*-350* have been assigned to leaves no longer present in the volume (as per historic foliation practices at Cambridge University Library). The conjectures behind these assignments were unreliable, perhaps reflecting erroneous ordering of the folios; the folio numbers with asterisks are probably the product of subsequent reassessment, hence the fact that they sometimes overlap with others. Notably, a note on f. 146v indicates that the following ff. 147-164 were missing, but in fact it is followed by ff. 148*-164*. The exent of the missing text suggests that the present foliation with asterisks is correct. In places the folio numbers have been struck through and replaced.

binding.p: Modern conservation binding, Cambridge University Library 2021, with red full leather covering over wooden boards.
The pieces of the former binding, of early modern western European origin, have been retained, and are housed with the manuscript.

The manuscript has been rebound a number of times. There is evidence of a number of stages of sewing, with eight sewing stations visible along the spine, including four early v-notches and later piercing. There is also evidence of cord sewing supports on the boards.
There are no visible endband remnants and no evidence of spine lining.

Laid paper endleaves, separate from the textblock; however due to the condition of the binding it is difficult to ascertain whether they were sewn or tipped. Both endleaves consist of a bifolio, one folio acting as a pastedown. A loose paper folio is also present at the right endleaves; this folio is made of a similar paper.

Couched-laminate boards with back cornering, completely detached when examined. Previous board attachment with three laced-in cords. Board dimensions are larger than the textblock, suggesting there might have been small squares of approximately 5mm on three edges.

Full covering of light brown reverse leather with lapped turn-ins with the fore-edge over. The spine was completely missing. Blind tooling decoration on both boards. Double fillet border with a double fillet inner frame, which include an inner decorative roll. Four decorative fleurons are blind tooled at the corners of the frame.

accMat.p: Four paper endleaves from the previous binding are preserved along with the manuscript; one bears notes in pencil regarding the kathismata. Small scraps of material detached during the rebinding in 2020-21 are also preserved.

history.provenance: The provenance of this manuscript is unclear.
history.acquisition: The manuscript had been acquired by Cambridge University Library by 1886, as indicated by the presence of annotations by the University Librarian Henry Bradshaw.

recordHist.source: Description draws upon unpublished notes by Patricia E. Easterling. Description of binding draws upon unpublished description prepared (2020) by Samuel Foley and Cecilia Diminuco, Dept of Conservation and Collection Care, Cambridge University Library.

availability.p: Entry to read in the Library is permitted only on presentation of a valid reader's card. For information on eligibility and admissions procedures, see Joining the Library). For further information on the availability of the manuscript, please contact the Manuscripts Reading Room.

supportDesc.condition: Almost all of f. 358* has been torn away. There have been losses to the lower and outer parts of many folios, some of them substantial and involving loss of text, some of which have been repaired with paper patches. There are long tears across some folios, which have been repaired with Japanese paper. There is extensive water staining and areas of dirt, and ink has been substantially abraded in places (e.g. f. 117*v).

handNote.p: ff. 34r-112v, 129r-146v, 165r-268r and 271r-340v were copied by Hand A, in mixed minuscule script, upright or slanting slightly to the right, in black ink, with significant variation in letter size and some flourishing of tails into the margin.

Syllabic abbreviations and superscript word endings appear only at the end of lines. Breathings are round and mute iota is absent. There is decorative use of the double dot and accentuation of all lengths of nomina sacra.

The flat-bottomed omega is present. Majuscule beta often appears in a heart-shaped form. Majuscule kappa often appears in an enlarged form with an extended downward diagonal with a long upturn at its end.

Punctuation used includes the middle and upper points, lower and middle commas and full stop. Punctuation at the end of lines of verse is often marked in red ink and widely separated from the last word.
Headings are written in Alexandrine majuscule script in red ink. The heading on f. 165 is in epigraphic display majuscule, in red ink.
ff. 113*r-131*v, 148*r-168*v and ff. 342*r-360*r were copied by Hand B, in mixed minuscule script, upright or slanting slightly to the right, in black ink, with significant variation in letter size.

Syllabic abbreviations and superscript word endings appear only at the end of lines. Breathings are round and mute iota is absent. There is decorative use of the double dot and accentuation of all lengths of nomina sacra.
The modern eta and flat-bottomed omega is present.
Punctuation used includes the middle and upper points and full stop.
Headings are written in the same style in red ink.
f. 268v was copied by Hand C, in a blocky, somewhat unsteady mixed minuscule script with variable slant, in black ink, with modest variation in letter size.
Syllabic abbreviations and superscript word endings appear throughout the line. Breathings are round and mute iota is absent. There is accentuation of all lengths of nomina sacra.
Punctuation used includes the middle and upper points and full stop.

decoDesc.decoNote: Rectangular headpieces in red ink precede psalms at the beginning of each kathisma on ff. 47r, 63v, 79v, 98r, 131v, 185v, 202v, 218r, 234r, 254v, 272v, 289v. On 131v only the border of the headpiece was drawn, and ornament added within it in black ink by a later hand. The same occurred on f. 325r. On f. 165r a large square border was drawn for a headpiece but also apparently left empty before half of it was filled with a black ink drawing of Moses, probably by a later hand. Another hand later added another, much cruder drawing, apparently based on the first one.

Minor initials in red ink, with simple ornament, begin each line of verse, with slightly larger, ornamented initials at the beginning of each psalm, ode, troparion or prayer. Those at the beginning of the first psalm of each kathisma are often larger and more elaborate.

additions.p: As part of the original production of the manuscript, the scribe has added marginal psalm numbers, marks for each doxa, kathisma numbers, the hours at which each kathisma was to be chanted and the echos number for each troparion.
There are occasional marginal Greek annotations and pen-trials (e.g. ff. 88v, 105v, 124*r).
Notes in English, in pencil, have been added regarding lost folios, by Henry Bradshaw (1831-1886) Bradshaw, Henry, 1831-1886 , University Librarian 1867-1886.

history.origin: The manuscript was probably produced in the second half of the 12th century, as suggested by the style of script. The very black ink and thickness of the pen used may suggest an origin in Cyprus or the the Levant.
